            <fr:title text="What is a formal system">What is a formal system</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Note</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A formal language, combined with rules that dictate what sorts of propositions are true and false within its context. Usually a formal system is designed in such a way that False is not a theorem. Formal systems usually include axioms as well.</html:p>
            <html:p>A formal system could be the system of simple arithmetic, say <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\set {0, 1, +}]]></fr:tex>, along with some rules about how plus works, say <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  n. n + 0 = n]]></fr:tex> (any number plus zero is that number).</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:uri>https://bord-o.github.io/0021/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>0021</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/0021/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="What is an axiom">What is an axiom</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Note</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>An axiom is something that you believe is true without a proof.</html:p>
                <html:p><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  n. n = n]]></fr:tex> (for any number, that number is equal to itself).</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:uri>https://bord-o.github.io/0022/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>0022</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/0022/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="What is a formal language">What is a formal language</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Note</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A set of symbols and words for very precisely describing something. This can be something like arithmetic (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[+, -, /]]></fr:tex>), or propositional calculus (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land ]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\to ]]></fr:tex>). Where in written language, the same words can mean different things based on the words and punctuation around them, in a formal language the same symbols/words mean the same thing every time they are used.</html:p>
                <html:p>e.g. A language of simple arithmetic, where we have variables, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a, b, c]]></fr:tex>, a binary operator <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[+]]></fr:tex>, and parenthesis to group expressions. This would allow me to write things like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(a + b) + c]]></fr:tex>, but not <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a + (+ b)]]></fr:tex></html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
